Summaries for BDH1 Gene

Entrez Gene Summary for BDH1 Gene

  • This gene encodes a member of the short-chain dehydrogenase/reductase gene family. The encoded protein forms a homotetrameric lipid-requiring enzyme of the mitochondrial membrane and has a specific requirement for phosphatidylcholine for optimal enzymatic activity. The encoded protein catalyzes the interconversion of acetoacetate and (R)-3-hydroxybutyrate, the two major ketone bodies produced during fatty acid catabolism. Alternatively spliced transcript variants encoding the same protein have been described. [provided by RefSeq, Jul 2008]

GeneCards Summary for BDH1 Gene

BDH1 (3-Hydroxybutyrate Dehydrogenase, Type 1) is a Protein Coding gene. Diseases associated with BDH1 include chromosome 3q29 microduplication syndrome. Among its related pathways are Butanoate metabolism and Metabolism. GO annotations related to this gene include oxidoreductase activity and 3-hydroxybutyrate dehydrogenase activity. An important paralog of this gene is HSD11B2.

Gene Wiki entry for BDH1 Gene

Molecular function for BDH1 Gene

UniProtKB/Swiss-Prot CatalyticActivity:
(R)-3-hydroxybutanoate + NAD(+) = acetoacetate + NADH.
  • BDH_HUMAN,Q02338
UniProtKB/Swiss-Prot EnzymeRegulation:
Requires phosphatidylcholine as an allosteric activator for enzymatic activity.
  • BDH_HUMAN,Q02338
